
<h2>1 20, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Dwight D. Eisenhower is inaugurated as the thirty-fourth President of the United States.</p>
<h2>1 27, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Ralph Ellison wins a National Book Award for Invisible Man. </p>
<h2>3 5, 1953</h2>"",""<p>The Soviet Union announces the death of Josef Stalin. </p>
<h2>3 17, 1953</h2>"",""<p>All price controls officially ended by the Office of Price Stabilization. </p>
<h2>4 1, 1953</h2>"",""<p>The Department of Health, Education, and Welfare is created by joint congressional action. </p>
<h2>4 16, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower delivers his "Chance for Peace" speech to the American Society of Newspaper Editors. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs the Submerged Lands Act. </p>
<h2>6 19, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Julius and Ethel Rosenberg are executed. </p>
<h2>7 26, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower addresses the American public and announces an armistice in Korea. </p>
<h2>8 1, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower proposes broadening the provisions of the Social Security Act to cover more than 10 million additional Americans. </p>
<h2>8 7, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs the Refugee Relief Act of 1953, admitting 214,000 more immigrants than permitted under existing immigration quotas. </p>
<h2>8 19, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Iranians, with the backing of the CIA, overthrow the government of Prime Minister Mohammed Mossadegh, ensuring Mohammed Reza Shah Pahlavi's hold on power. </p>
<h2>9 10, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Secretary of Labor Martin Durkin resigns, in large part to protest the failure of the Eisenhower Administration to propose amendments to the Taft-Hartley Act. </p>
<h2>9 30, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower appoints Earl Warren chief justice of the Supreme Court. </p>
<h2>10 8, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower announces that the Soviet Union has tested a hydrogen bomb. </p>
<h2>12 8, 1953</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower gives his "Atoms for Peace" speech to the U.N. General Assembly in New York. </p>
<h2>1 11, 1954</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower sends a special message to Congress asking for changes in the Taft-Hartley labor law. </p>
<h2>3 8, 1954</h2>"",""<p>The United States and Japan sign a mutual defense agreement that provides for the gradual and partial rearmament of Japan. </p>
<h2>4 23, 1954</h2>"6 17, 1954",""<p>The Army-McCarthy hearings begin and continue for two months. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>France surrenders its garrison at Dien Bien Phu to the Vietminh. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs the St. Lawrence Seaway Bill. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>The Supreme Court announces a decision in <i>Brown v. Topeka Board of Education</i>, ruling that racial segregation in public schools is unconstitutional. </p>
<h2>6 18, 1954</h2>"",""<p>A CIA-sponsored coup in Guatemala overthrows the government of Jacobo Arbenz Guzman. </p>
<h2>7 11, 1954</h2>"",""<p>The first "White Citizens Council" is organized in Indianola, Mississippi. </p>
<h2>7 21, 1954</h2>"",""<p>The Geneva Accords are signed, establishing a cease-fire and partition of Vietnam. The United States refuses to sign. </p>
<h2>9 8, 1954</h2>"",""<p>The United States signs the SEATO (South East Asian Treaty Organization) Pact. </p>
<h2>11 2, 1954</h2>"",""<p>The Democratic Party narrowly regains control of both houses of Congress. </p>
<h2>12 2, 1954</h2>"",""<p>The United States signs a mutual defense pact with Taiwan. </p>
<h2>12 2, 1954</h2>"",""<p>The Senate votes to censure Senator Joseph McCarthy (R-WI). </p>
<h2>1 10, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Chinese Communist Air Force raid the nationalist-controlled Tachen Islands and seize Ichiang Island. </p>
<h2>1 19, 1955</h2>"",""<p>The first filming of a presidential press conference. </p>
<h2>1 21, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower meets with Secretary of State Dulles and Secretary of Defense Wilson to discuss a resolution that would authorize the U.S. defense of Taiwan and the Pescadores. Congress approves the resolution on January 28. </p>
<h2>3 16, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower announces that the United States would use atomic weapons in the event of war with Communist China. </p>
<h2>4 11, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Roy Wilkins becomes Executive Secretary of the NAACP, succeeding Walter White. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>In <i>Brown II</i>, the Supreme Court orders schools integrated "with all deliberate speed." </p>
<h2>7 12, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower tells congressional leaders that the Geneva Conference will not be another Yalta. </p>
<h2>7 18, 1955</h2>"",""<p>The Geneva Conference opens, attended by the heads of state of Britain, France, the U.S.S.R, and the United States. </p>
<h2>7 21, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower makes his "open skies" proposal at Geneva. </p>
<h2>7 29, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Plans for the first artificial satellites, scheduled to be launched in 1957, are announced by the United States. </p>
<h2>8 28, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Fourteen-year old Emmett Till is kidnapped and murdered in Money, Mississippi. </p>
<h2>9 24, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower suffers a "moderate" heart attack in Denver, Colorado. </p>
<h2>10 10, 1955</h2>"",""<p>The Supreme Court orders Autherine Lucy admitted to the University of Alabama. </p>
<h2>11 15, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Adlai Stevenson announces that he will run for President in 1956. </p>
<h2>11 25, 1955</h2>"",""<p> The Interstate Commerce Commission bans racial segregation on interstate trains and buses. </p>
<h2>12 1, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Rosa Parks is arrested in Montgomery, Alabama, for refusing to give up her seat on a bus to a white man. During the following week, the Montgomery African American community, led by Reverend Martin Luther King Jr., organizes a boycott of the city's buses that lasts for more than a year. </p>
<h2>12 5, 1955</h2>"",""<p>The merger of the American Federation of Labor (AFL) and the Congress of Industrial Organizations (CIO) is ratified. </p>
<h2>12 26, 1955</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower tries to persuade Richard Nixon to take a cabinet post and not stand for re-election in 1956 as vice president. </p>
<h2>1 30, 1956</h2>"",""<p>African American student Autherine Lucy is admitted to the University of Alabama following a court order. </p>
<h2>2 22, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower releases $1 billion worth of Uranium-235 for peaceful atomic purposes. </p>
<h2>2 29, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower announces that he will run for a second term as President. </p>
<h2>3 12, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Nineteen senators and eighty-one representatives sign the "Southern Manifesto," promising to use "all lawful means" to reverse the <i>Brown</i> decisions. </p>
<h2>4 9, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower again urges Nixon to take a cabinet post. </p>
<h2>4 25, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower announces that Nixon will be his running mate in 1956. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower approves U-2 spy flights over the Soviet Union. </p>
<h2>6 4, 1956</h2>"",""<p>In <i>Browder v. Gayle</i>, a three-judge district court rules that bus segregation in Montgomery, Alabama, is unconstitutional.  </p>
<h2>6 29, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs the Federal Aid Highway Act, providing federal funding for the construction of a system of interstate highways for transportation and national defense. </p>
<h2>7 26, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Egyptian president Gamal Abdel Nasser nationalizes the Suez Canal. </p>
<h2>8 1, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs the Social Security Act, permitting women to retire at age sixty-two and disabled workers at age fifty. </p>
<h2>8 1, 1956</h2>"",""<p>The recently discovered Salk Polio Vaccine is sold on the open market. </p>
<h2>8 17, 1956</h2>"",""<p>The Democratic National Convention nominates Adlai Stevenson for President. </p>
<h2>8 21, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower attends the Republican National Convention and accepts nomination as the party's candidate for President. </p>
<h2>9 29, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower appoints William J. Brennan to the Supreme Court. </p>
<h2>10 22, 1956</h2>"",""<p>The Hungarian Revolution begins. </p>
<h2>10 31, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Israel, Britain, and France attack Egypt; Eisenhower condemns the attack. </p>
<h2>11 4, 1956</h2>"",""<p>The Soviet Union crushes the Hungarian Revolution via armed intervention. </p>
<h2>11 5, 1956</h2>"",""<p>A cease-fire is established in Egypt. </p>
<h2>11 6, 1956</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower defeats Stevenson by nine million votes to win a second term. Congress remains in the hands of the Democratic Party. </p>
<h2>11 13, 1956</h2>"",""<p><i>Browder v. Gayle</i> is upheld by the Supreme Court. </p>
<h2>12 20, 1956</h2>"",""<p>The Montgomery Bus Boycott comes to an end. </p>
<h2>1 5, 1957</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower proposes the "Eisenhower Doctrine" regarding defense of the Middle East. </p>
<h2>1 6, 1957</h2>"",""<p>Elvis Presley makes his third appearance on the Ed Sullivan Show; and concern that his gyrating dance style is too lewd lead network executives to show him only from the waist up. </p>
<h2>1 20, 1957</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower is inaugurated for a second term as President. </p>
<h2>2 14, 1957</h2>"",""<p>The Southern Christian Leadership Conference (SCLC) is organized in New Orleans. Martin Luther King, Jr., is elected president of the organization. </p>
<h2>3 7, 1957</h2>"",""<p>Congress sanctions the "Eisenhower Doctrine." </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>John F. Kennedy wins a Pulitzer Prize for his book <i>Profiles in Courage</i>. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>Secretary of the Treasury George Humphrey resigns; Eisenhower selects Robert B. Anderson as his replacement. </p>
<h2>7 12, 1957</h2>"",""<p>The Surgeon General reports that scientific research has established a link between cigarette smoking and lung cancer. </p>
<h2>8 30, 1957</h2>"",""<p>Senator Strom Thurmond (D-SC) filibusters against pending civil rights legislation for a record twenty-four hours, twenty-seven minutes. </p>
<h2>9 9, 1957</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs the Civil Rights Act of 1957, the first civil rights bill since Reconstruction. </p>
<h2>9 24, 1957</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower orders federal troops to Little Rock, Arkansas, to end the school desegregation crisis. </p>
<h2>10 4, 1957</h2>"",""<p>The Soviet Union launches <i>Sputnik</i>. </p>
<h2>11 25, 1957</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower suffers a vascular spasm. </p>
<h2>1 27, 1958</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower asks Congress for federal aid for education. </p>
<h2>4 1, 1958</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs legislation he hopes will stimulate housing construction and help combat a developing economic recession. </p>
<h2>4 2, 1958</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower recommends the formation of a civilian agency to direct space exploration. </p>
<h2>4 27, 1958</h2>"",""<p>Vice President Nixon embarks on an eighteen-day tour of Latin America. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower orders 1,000 troops from Caribbean bases to rescue Nixon, if necessary, after the Vice President was threatened on his tour of Latin America. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower doubles the strength of the Sixth Fleet in the Mediterranean. </p>
<h2>6 23, 1958</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower meets with African American leaders Martin Luther King, Roy Wilkins, A. Philip Randolph, and Lester Granger. </p>	
<h2>7 7, 1958</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs a bill making Alaska the forty-ninth state. </p>
<h2>7 15, 1958</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower orders the U.S. Marines into Lebanon. </p>
<h2>8 23, 1958</h2>"",""<p>The People's Republic of China resumes the shelling of Nationalist Chinese islands Quemoy and Matsu. </p>
<h2>9 22, 1958</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower accepts the resignation of Sherman Adams, his chief of staff, after Adams is found to have accepted improper gifts from businessmen. </p>
<h2>10 25, 1958</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower orders the withdrawal of the last U.S. Marines from Lebanon. </p>
<h2>9 2, 1958</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs the National Defense Education Act. </p>
<h2>1 1, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Fidel Castro's revolutionaries overthrow Cuban dictator Fulgencio Batista. </p>
<h2>3 18, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs a bill admitting Hawaii as the fiftieth state. </p>
<h2>4 13, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower asks Nikita Khrushchev for a partial test-ban agreement. </p>
<h2>4 15, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Secretary of State John Foster Dulles resigns because of illness; he dies on May 24. </p>
<h2>4 18, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower names Christian Herter secretary of state. </p>
<h2>4 25, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower, with Queen Elizabeth, dedicates the St. Lawrence Seaway. </p>
<h2>7 15, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower refuses to seek a Taft-Hartley injunction to end the steelworkers strike. </p>
<h2>7 24, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Nixon and Khrushchev have their "kitchen debate" in Moscow. </p>
<h2>9 14, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs the Landrum-Griffin Act, legislation meant to combat growing corruption in labor organizations. </p>
<h2>9 27, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Khrushchev visits the United States and meets with Eisenhower at Camp David on September 25 and 26. </p>
<h2>10 6, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower invokes a Taft-Hartley injunction in the dockworkers strike. </p>
<h2>10 19, 1959</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower invokes a Taft-Hartley injunction in the steelworkers strike. </p>
<h2>1 2, 1960</h2>"",""<p>Senator John F. Kennedy announces his candidacy for the Democratic presidential nomination. </p>
<h2>1 4, 1960</h2>"",""<p>The Steelworkers strike ends with a settlement. </p>
<h2>1 9, 1960</h2>"",""<p>Vice President Nixon announces his candidacy for the Republican presidential nomination. </p>
<h2>1 13, 1960</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower declares his support for Nixon. </p>
<h2>2 1, 1960</h2>"",""<p>Civil rights sit-ins begin in Greensboro, North Carolina. </p>
<h2>3 17, 1960</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower authorizes the CIA to begin training exiles to invade Cuba. </p>
<h2>4 17, 1960</h2>"",""<p>The Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC), a civil rights group born out of the sit-in demonstrations, organizes in Raleigh, North Carolina. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>The Soviet Union announces that is has shot down an American U-2 spy plane. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower signs the Civil Rights Act of 1960. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower acknowledges that the United States has been conducting U-2 spy flights over the Soviet Union. Khrushchev announces that Francis Gary Powers, a downed U-2 pilot, has admitted to spying on the Soviet Union. </p>
<h2>5 </h2>"",""<p>The Paris Summit between the Soviet Union and the United States ends when Eisenhower refuses to apologize for the U-2 flights and Khrushchev refuses to meet with the President. </p>
<h2>7 13, 1960</h2>"",""<p>Kennedy receives the Democratic presidential nomination. </p>
<h2>7 27, 1960</h2>"",""<p>Nixon receives the Republican presidential nomination. </p>
<h2>9 7, 1960</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower asks the Soviet Union to stop supporting Patrice Lumumba in the Congo. </p>
<h2>9 26, 1960</h2>"",""<p>John F. Kennedy and Richard Nixon hold the first televised presidential debate. </p>
<h2>11 8, 1960</h2>"",""<p>Kennedy defeats Nixon in the presidential election. </p>
<h2>1 3, 1961</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower severs diplomatic relations with Cuba. </p>
<h2>1 17, 1961</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower's farewell address warns the nation of the growing power of the American "military industrial complex." </p>
<h2>1 20, 1961</h2>"",""<p>Eisenhower leaves Washington for his Gettysburg farm. </p>
